    "rawMarkdown": "Isn't the goal for this competition to make a model that memorizes the input and output pattern as much as possible without generalizing? That would be the optimal golf solution.",
    "content": "<p>Isn't the goal for this competition to make a model that memorizes the input and output pattern as much as possible without generalizing? That would be the optimal golf solution.</p>",
    "replies": [
     {
      "id": 3447407,
      "postDate": "2026-04-23T04:56:34.550Z",
      "rawMarkdown": "not memorise. the goal is to synthesize a specific program.\n\ni give you one example:\n\n```\ncorrect logic is y= 2*x\n\nexamples data: (x,y) = (1,2),(2,4)\n\npossible correct solutions:\n1)  y=2x graph\n2) y= LUT(x) where LUT entries are y=2x #correct memoristion\n\n\nso if hidden data is x=3, all the above models are correct\n\n\nwrong solution\n1)  y=x*x graph\nthen he cheat: if x==1,y=2\n\nso if hidden data is x=3, this model is arong\n\n\n```\n",
      "content": "<p>not memorise. the goal is to synthesize a specific program.</p>\n<p>i give you one example:</p>\n<pre><code>correct logic is y= 2*x\n\nexamples data: (x,y) = (1,2),(2,4)\n\npossible correct solutions:\n1)  y=2x graph\n2) y= LUT(x) where LUT entries are y=2x #correct memoristion\n\n\nso if hidden data is x=3, all the above models are correct\n\n\nwrong solution\n1)  y=x*x graph\nthen he cheat: if x==1,y=2\n\nso if hidden data is x=3, this model is arong\n</code></pre>",
